The Balkans, also known as the Balkan Peninsula or Balkan region, is a geographic area in southeastern Europe. It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea, the Mediterranean, the Aegean Sea, and the Black Sea. The region is named after the Balkan Mountains which run through Bulgaria and Serbia. The Balkans includes countries such as Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Greece, Kosovo, Montenegro, North Macedonia, Romania, Serbia, and Slovenia. The region has a diverse history and culture, with influences from various empires and civilizations including the Roman, Byzantine, Ottoman, and Austro-Hungarian empires.